# Setting up Redmine in cPanel - Ruby on Rails


In this tutorial, we are going to be setting up Redmine in cPanel, a popular free open source ruby application.  In order to do this, you will need shell access, as well as access to your cPanel account.

Let's get started!
**1) Setting up the database**

  1. Login to cPanel, and go to the Databases area, click on the "MySQL Databases" icon
  1. In the "Create New Database" text box type the new database name, and click on the "Create Database" button.
  
  ```diagram

```
  3. Next after the database is created, we need to create a database User.  In the "Add New User" section of the MySQL Databases area in cPanel, enter a username and a password, don't forget to write this password down somewhere!
  

```diagram

```

  
  4. Next we need to add this new database user to the database.  In the "Add User To Database" area of the MySQL databases section in cPanel, select the username and database name from the respective drop down menus and click on "Add"
  
```diagram

```
  
  5. After clicking the "Add" button, this is going to open the next screen.  Click on the "ALL PRIVLEDGES" option, which will check all of the boxes for you, and click "Make Changes" You will see a confirmation page after doing this.  Now  your new database user will be able to access the empty database we've created for your instance of Redmine.
  
```diagram

```
  
**2)  Setting up the Ruby Application in cPanel**.

1. Once the database is setup, click on the Home icon at the top of cPanel, then browse down to the Software/Services area, and click on the "Ruby on Rails" icon.
1. Enter the name of your application, in this example, we are using "redmine"
1. Make sure to click on the "Load on Boot" checkbox
1. The application path will autoload.  This is referring to your home directory, and will be located, at this example in: /home/rubytest/rails_apps/redmine
1. Select the Environment as "Production"
1. Click on the "Create" button

```diagram

```


7. You will see a confirmation page, click on "Go Back" to go back to the Ruby on Rails area of cPanel.  Now you will see the application in cPanel, if it is running after its creation, click on the "Stop" button

```diagram

```

**3)  Shell level commands**

- At this step in the process we are now ready to login to the server via SSH as your user via a terminal.  If you are using Windows, I may suggest PuTTY, a popular terminal application to connect.  You will use your cPanel login credentials as the username and password.
- Now we will change the directory to the location of your ruby application.  Run the following in your terminal

```
cd ~/rails_apps/redmine/
```

- If you run the command "ls" you will see that cPanel has put a bunch of files and folders in this directory, which happened when you created the ruby application in cPanel. Because we are using redmine, lets    remove the pre-created contents.  Use caution when typing this command at the command line.  It removes all files and folders in the directory you are currently in. Better to make backup first

```
# cp -r redmine redmine.orig
# rm -rf *
```

- Now that your rails application folder is empty, lets double check the ruby and rails version on the server, with the following two commands:

```
root@server1 [/home/wilmethg/rails_apps/Redmine]# ruby -v
ruby 1.8.7 (2012-06-29 patchlevel 370) [i686-linux]
root@server1 [/home/wilmethg/rails_apps/Redmine]# rails -v
Rails 2.3.18
```

**4)  Configuration Time (At the Shell)**!

- To get things working in our redmine application, we need to change some things regarding the redmine configuration files.  If you run in the command line "pwd" you will see your current directory is /home/username/rails_apps/redmine
- Next we have to copy  an example database configuration file and configure the database settings.  In the command line run:

```
cp config/database.yml.example config/database.yml
```
to copy the example file to a file in the config folder called "database.yml"

- Edit the database.yml file to use the database username and password we've setup in Step 1.

```
nano config/database.yml
```

Here, were are going to edit the top portion in the "production" section.  After editing it may look something like this:

```
production:
adapter: mysql
database: rubytest_redmine
host: localhost
username: rubytest_redmine
password: supersecretpassword
encoding: utf8
```
ake note, you will be updating the "database" "username" and "password" lines of this.  Save and exit from the text editor once completed. **Be sure there is space after colon ( : ) otherwise it will end up with error**.

- Next we need to run a command at the command line to create the session store for your ruby application.  Run the following in your terminal:

```
RAILS_ENV=production rake config/initializers/session_store.rb
```

If you get error like

```
root@server1 [/home/wilmethg/rails_apps/Redmine]# RAILS_ENV=production rake config/initializers/session_store.rb
Some gems may need to be installed or updated.
Please run `bundle install --without development test`.
```

Then run

```
root@server1 [/home/wilmethg/rails_apps/Redmine]# bundle install --without development test postgresql
```

**5) Lastly, we need to populate the empty database with the default redmine data, run the following commands in your terminal**:

```

RAILS_ENV=production rake db:migrate
RAILS_ENV=production rake redmine:load_default_data
```

At this point, If you get error like below, then it means you didnt follow Step # 3 properly. Re-read Step # 3 and make sure there is space after colon ( : )

**5) Finishing up**

One thing to keep in mind about ruby, is that it runs on a different port than your normal Apache application, it runs on port 12001.  To avoid having your website go to http://domain.com:12001 when you go to the website, let's go back to cPanel and create a re-write rule, so that you only see http://domain.com when going to the ruby application.

1. Once back into cPanel, go to the Ruby on Rails icon from the Software/Services area.
1. In the Create a Rewrite area, click on the "Create Rewrite" button next to your ruby application name

```diagram

```

3. This will take you to the next screen.  You can leave the textbox blank if you want to load the application from your main domain only and click on save

```diagram

```


4. After this you will see the rewrite information in the "Current Rewrites" area of your Ruby on Rails section in cPanel.
5. In the "Available Ruby on Rails Applications" section in cPanel, click on the green circle "RUN" button next to your application name to start the application
6. After the application is running, you can visit your newly setup ruby application in your web browser!
7. You can click on login and use default login
username: admin
password: admin
